{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17528835","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17528835"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T15:47:31+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T15:47:31+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14332"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"14332","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/14332"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.2,0.3,0.31,0.03,0.16]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7027"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"79471"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"7027","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/7027"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14332"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"64793"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"13"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"65"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"2375"},{"type":"tags","id":"2436"},{"type":"tags","id":"3748"},{"type":"tags","id":"3751"},{"type":"tags","id":"4965"},{"type":"tags","id":"9270"},{"type":"tags","id":"9278"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"12920"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"16718"},{"type":"contributions","id":"44312"},{"type":"contributions","id":"48161"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"79471","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/79471"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 25-year-old woman presents to the General Practice clinic with fatigue and yellowing of her eyes for the past two weeks. She has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications. Her parent mentions that several family members have had their spleens removed. On examination, she appears pale and mildly jaundiced. Her pulse rate is 90/min, blood pressure 120/75 mmHg, respiratory rate 16/min, SpO2 98% on room air, and temperature 36.7\u00b0C. Abdominal examination reveals a palpable spleen 3 cm below the costal margin.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EInvestigations reveal:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003EHaemoglobin: 95 g/L (115-165)\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003EMean corpuscular volume (MCV): 85 fL (80-100)\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003EMean corpuscular haemoglobin concentration (MCHC): 360 g/L (310-350)\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003EReticulocyte count: 8% (0.5-2.5)\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003ETotal bilirubin: 35 \u00b5mol/L (3-20)\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA peripheral blood smear shows numerous spherocytes.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate next investigation to confirm the diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Glucose-6-phosphate dehydrogenase testing","Eosin-5\u0027-maleimide (EMA) binding test","Osmotic fragility test","Urinary haemosiderin","Haemoglobin electrophoresis"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient\u0027s presentation is highly suggestive of hereditary spherocytosis (HS). The combination of anaemia, jaundice, splenomegaly, family history of splenectomy, and the presence of spherocytes on the peripheral blood smear are classic features of this condition. HS is an inherited disorder of red blood cell membrane proteins, leading to the formation of spherical erythrocytes that are prone to premature destruction in the spleen.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Eeosin-5\u0027-maleimide (EMA) binding test\u003C/strong\u003E is currently considered the most sensitive and specific diagnostic test for HS. This flow cytometry-based test measures the fluorescence intensity of EMA-labeled red blood cells. In HS, there is a reduction in EMA binding due to the deficiency of membrane proteins, particularly band 3. The EMA binding test has a sensitivity and specificity of over 90% for HS diagnosis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Eosmotic fragility test\u003C/strong\u003E was traditionally used to diagnose HS but has largely been replaced by more sensitive and specific tests like the EMA binding test. The osmotic fragility test measures the susceptibility of red blood cells to lysis in hypotonic solutions. While it can be positive in HS, it lacks sensitivity, especially in mild cases, and can be positive in other conditions.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EGlucose-6-phosphate dehydrogenase (G6PD) testing\u003C/strong\u003E is used to diagnose G6PD deficiency, an X-linked disorder that can cause acute haemolytic anaemia, particularly after exposure to certain medications or foods. While G6PD deficiency can cause haemolysis, it typically does not present with chronic anaemia, splenomegaly, or spherocytes on the blood smear, making it less likely in this case.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EHaemoglobin electrophoresis\u003C/strong\u003E is used to diagnose haemoglobinopathies such as sickle cell disease or thalassemia. While these conditions can also cause anaemia, the clinical presentation and peripheral blood smear findings in this case are not consistent with these disorders.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EUrinary haemosiderin\u003C/strong\u003E testing is used to detect chronic intravascular haemolysis. While it can be positive in some haemolytic anaemias, it is not specific for hereditary spherocytosis and is not the most appropriate next step in this case. HS primarily causes extravascular haemolysis in the spleen, rather than intravascular haemolysis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIn summary, given the high clinical suspicion of hereditary spherocytosis, the eosin-5\u0027-maleimide (EMA) binding test is the most appropriate next investigation to confirm the diagnosis due to its high sensitivity and specificity for this condition.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Hereditary spherocytosis is characterised by anaemia, jaundice, and splenomegaly.","The peripheral blood smear in hereditary spherocytosis typically shows many spherocytes.","The eosin-5\u0027-maleimide (EMA) binding test is a sensitive and specific diagnostic test for hereditary spherocytosis."],"references":["Risinger M, Kalfa TA. Red cell membrane disorders: structure meets function. Blood. 2020;136(11):1250-1261. doi:10.1182/blood.2019000946"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"64793"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14332"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"64793","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/64793"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-01-14T19:38:16+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-01-14T19:39:56+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7027"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"79471"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"13","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/13"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\ude78","name":"Haematology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:44+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"25","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/25"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc68\u200d\ud83d\udc69\u200d\ud83d\udc66","name":"General Practice","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"6"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"65","links":{"self":"h